textDisplay: Got you some quite interesting feature suggestions for the game, just for the sake of making it spicier, try randomizing the behavior of the customers, for example (most will behave normally, but some will be impatient while waiting, some more patient, some might be a little too aggressive, one in a bunch will try to leave without paying, and one will try to assault you with a gun and take some of your cash)The player should have the chance to attack and defend themselves with some weapon against robbers & be able to get killed & lose cash.Might be a lot of work tho, but honestly, I don't see much to do on serving beverages to customers endlessly.
textOriginal:
Got you some quite interesting feature suggestions for the game, just for the sake of making it spicier, try randomizing the behavior of the customers, for example (most will behave normally, but some will be impatient while waiting, some more patient, some might be a little too aggressive, one in a bunch will try to leave without paying, and one will try to assault you with a gun and take some of your cash)

The player should have the chance to attack and defend themselves with some weapon against robbers & be able to get killed & lose cash.

Might be a lot of work tho, but honestly, I don't see much to do on serving beverages to customers endlessly.
videoTitle: How I made my NPCs feel immersive using Unity's Animation Rigging! Tavern Team Devlog 2
cleaned_comment:
got you some quite interesting feature suggestions for the game, just for the sake of making it spicier, try randomizing the behavior of the customers, for example (most will behave normally, but some will be impatient while waiting, some more patient, some might be a little too aggressive, one in a bunch will try to leave without paying, and one will try to assault you with a gun and take some of your cash)

the player should have the chance to attack and defend themselves with some weapon against robbers & be able to get killed & lose cash.

might be a lot of work tho, but honestly, i don't see much to do on serving beverages to customers endlessly.

textDisplay: You should add recruiter NPCs that come into the tavern and talk to young people and try to convince them of being adventurers.To add to that, you could add some form of challenge that would let you influence their effectiveness. Like if you fail to serve them and the young people start think about it carefully they refuse, but if you get them full of food and drinks they have a chance of agreeing.Also, now that you have adventurers, you could add different tiers like bronze, silver, gold, etc., and give them discounts or other benefits.A lot of medieval taverns also had rooms to sleep in, so you could get that sorted for them if you want.I realize this goes really far into what would be my vision so consider any of these suggestions with a grain of salt.
textOriginal:
You should add recruiter NPCs that come into the tavern and talk to young people and try to convince them of being adventurers.

To add to that, you could add some form of challenge that would let you influence their effectiveness. Like if you fail to serve them and the young people start think about it carefully they refuse, but if you get them full of food and drinks they have a chance of agreeing.

Also, now that you have adventurers, you could add different tiers like bronze, silver, gold, etc., and give them discounts or other benefits.

A lot of medieval taverns also had rooms to sleep in, so you could get that sorted for them if you want.

I realize this goes really far into what would be my vision so consider any of these suggestions with a grain of salt.
videoTitle: I added Infinite Replayability to my DREAM Game! | Tavern Team Devlog #6
cleaned_comment:
you should add recruiter npcs that come into the tavern and talk to young people and try to convince them of being adventurers.

to add to that, you could add some form of challenge that would let you influence their effectiveness. like if you failure to serve them and the young people start think about it carefully they refuse, but if you get them full of food and drinks they have a chance of agreeing.

also, now that you have adventurers, you could add different tiers like bronze, silver, gold, etc., and give them discounts or other benefits.

a lot of medieval taverns also had rooms to sleep in, so you could get that sorted for them if you want.

i realize this goes really far into what would be my vision so consider any of these suggestions with a grain of salt.

textDisplay: Here's an even simpler explanation for procedural generation (at least as it applies to Unity): I'm going to take a number and set that as Random.seed. This way every time we we pull from the number table (as random values truly aren't random and just use a giant table of numbers to query) we'll consistently get the same results for the values we plugged in. How do we get that initial number? Up to you. Could be based on the current date and time, or maybe the name of the users PC which you then converted to a hex value, or something else. Up to you.

textDisplay: Procedural generation is an interesting choice for this but I don't think the networking benefits are going to outweigh simply randomizing the different properties of each character on generation. (After all, it's only going to really matter when the character spawns/loads in to the scene and after that the data is irrelevant).If you do continue this route, you may want to have characters spawn in with similar sets of clothes depending on where they're from or what their profession is. It's possible to do this with noise values (similar to minecraft worldgen with the 7d noise or whatever), but it'll be a lot easier to maintain and explain to somebody else who may work on the project if you simply randomize from a set, and use dynamic sets of clothing and features for certain groups of people.One of the cons of using noise is that the randomness is very uniform and the uniqueness of every person winds up easily blending them in and making them look similar despite all the wild differences.
textOriginal:
Procedural generation is an interesting choice for this but I don't think the networking benefits are going to outweigh simply randomizing the different properties of each character on generation. (After all, it's only going to really matter when the character spawns/loads in to the scene and after that the data is irrelevant).

If you do continue this route, you may want to have characters spawn in with similar sets of clothes depending on where they're from or what their profession is. It's possible to do this with noise values (similar to minecraft worldgen with the 7d noise or whatever), but it'll be a lot easier to maintain and explain to somebody else who may work on the project if you simply randomize from a set, and use dynamic sets of clothing and features for certain groups of people.

One of the cons of using noise is that the randomness is very uniform and the uniqueness of every person winds up easily blending them in and making them look similar despite all the wild differences.
videoTitle: I added Infinite Replayability to my DREAM Game! | Tavern Team Devlog #6
cleaned_comment:
procedural generation is an interesting choice for this but i don't think the networking benefits are going to outweigh simply randomizing the different properties of each character on generation. (after all, it's only going to really matter when the character spawns/loads in to the scene and after that the data is irrelevant).

if you do continue this route, you may want to have characters spawn in with similar sets of clothes depending on where they're from or what their profession is. it's possible to do this with noise values (similar to minecraft worldgen with the 7 d noise or whatever), but it'll be a lot easier to maintain and explain to somebody else who may work on the project if you simply randomize from a set, and use dynamic sets of clothing and features for certain groups of people.

one of the cons of using noise is that the randomness is very uniform and the uniqueness of every person winds up easily blending them in and making them look similar despite all the wild differences.

textDisplay: This is coming along amazingly. I am catching up in your devlogs, but wanted to ask. I know you said the Player has to hire all of these workers, so the Player starts off running it all by themselves. Would it be possible for the workers to not be a permanent hiring? Meaning, if you fail to pay them their wage, and can and will quit, which could be horrific for the Player, especially depending on how much they upgraded the tavern and how many regulars they amassed. If a bartender (How many can you have? Can you upgrade the bar to be bigger with up to 3 bartenders to handle the influx as you tavern grows more popular?) quits, you have to handle all those people, which may lead to them getting impatient and leaving, especially if you haven't directly served anyone in a while.These are just some of my thoughts after watching, though sorry for how long that got. I wish you luck on the rest of your game! Can't wait to see what else you come up with and implement. Take care! 🙌👍

textDisplay: Someone here mentioned gambling. Would be cool to add an additional layer of multiplayer to have real people enter the pub to play cards games, magic tricks, that knife-finger game, perhaps? With that, adding incentives on making the night a success for the pub (making friends with the patrons, buying more drinks), or making the staff fail the night (spilling drinks, picking fights without getting removed from the bouncer).Edit: more ideas!Adding an intoxication level. Every pint increases how drunk the patrons/players are. The bouncer will need to monitor those who get to 4+ pints and remove them accordingly/bar tenders won’t be able to serve steaming people. The more drunk people, the more likely there is to be a brawl. There’s probably a lot you can do with this.Is there a goal for the night? Turning profits? Happy customers? How does your team win?I can also see a lot of potential for adding more races with unique attributes to increase difficulty. Ghouls who don’t drink and make everyone miserable, hobbits who are too short for the table/bar, orcs/bad guys who are aggressive and pick fights… what would wizards do? (Clearly LOTR inspired). Also love the idea of adding situational NPCs (kind of like modifiers).Real cool concept, looking forward to watching the progress.
textOriginal:
Someone here mentioned gambling. Would be cool to add an additional layer of multiplayer to have real people enter the pub to play cards games, magic tricks, that knife-finger game, perhaps? 

With that, adding incentives on making the night a success for the pub (making friends with the patrons, buying more drinks), or making the staff fail the night (spilling drinks, picking fights without getting removed from the bouncer).

Edit: more ideas!

Adding an intoxication level. Every pint increases how drunk the patrons/players are. The bouncer will need to monitor those who get to 4+ pints and remove them accordingly/bar tenders won’t be able to serve steaming people. The more drunk people, the more likely there is to be a brawl. There’s probably a lot you can do with this.

Is there a goal for the night? Turning profits? Happy customers? How does your team win?

I can also see a lot of potential for adding more races with unique attributes to increase difficulty. Ghouls who don’t drink and make everyone miserable, hobbits who are too short for the table/bar, orcs/bad guys who are aggressive and pick fights… what would wizards do? (Clearly LOTR inspired). Also love the idea of adding situational NPCs (kind of like modifiers).

Real cool concept, looking forward to watching the progress.
videoTitle: Forcing an AI to do my CHORES!  | Tavern Team Devlog #7

with that, adding incentives on making the night a success for the pub (making friends with the patrons, buying more drinks), or making the staff failure the night (spilling drinks, picking fights without getting removed from the bouncer).

edit: more ideas!

adding an intoxication level. every pint increases how drunk the patrons/players are. the bouncer will need to monitor those who get to 4+ pints and remove them accordingly/bar tenders won’t be able to serve steaming people. the more drunk people, the more likely there is to be a brawl. there’s probably a lot you can do with this.

is there a goal for the night? turning profits? happy customers? how does your team win?

i can also see a lot of potential for adding more races with unique attributes to increase difficulty. ghouls who don’t drink and make everyone miserable, hobbits who are too short for the table/bar, orcs/bad guys who are aggressive and pick fights… what would wizards do? (clearly lotr inspired). also love the idea of adding situational npcs (kind of like modifiers).

textDisplay: I like it. Here are some ideas to help your scope creep: - Rats as another chore- Negotiating minigame to upsell customers to the better Ale- Flair bartending minigame. (physics or quicktime events?)- Flirt option- Ability to move the furniture into different arrangements for customization- In-game achievements/events that make banners - eventually cover your walls with them like trophies.- Demo of game that allows you to visit another person's tavern as a guest - this would enable exposure as Streamers could run a bar and their audience/patrons visit and hang out there. Kind of meta. Would work well with more mini-games for patrons.- Trivia- Darts- Card game(s)- Drunkenness UI for when a Patron has had too much - gets worse at walking, darts, trivia; sounds change slightly, etc.
textOriginal:
I like it. Here are some ideas to help your scope creep: 
- Rats as another chore
- Negotiating minigame to upsell customers to the better Ale
- Flair bartending minigame. (physics or quicktime events?)
- Flirt option
- Ability to move the furniture into different arrangements for customization
- In-game achievements/events that make banners - eventually cover your walls with them like trophies.
- Demo of game that allows you to visit another person's tavern as a guest - this would enable exposure as Streamers could run a bar and their audience/patrons visit and hang out there. Kind of meta. Would work well with more mini-games for patrons.
- Trivia
- Darts
- Card game(s)
- Drunkenness UI for when a Patron has had too much - gets worse at walking, darts, trivia; sounds change slightly, etc.

textDisplay: You could have the customers behave more like real people by introducing market dynamics, for example by letting the player choose the prices for the items.then how much the customers spend and what type of customers come in would depend on the visuals of the bar and the prices.for example maybe you can upgrade your bar to look very luxurious, this would attract more wealthy clients who don't mind spending more.simultaneously by changing the price you could influence how much clients buy, simple supply and demand action.In my opinion having these more detailed modelling of clients' behavior is crucial to having depth to the game.
textOriginal:
You could have the customers behave more like real people by introducing market dynamics, for example by letting the player choose the prices for the items.
then how much the customers spend and what type of customers come in would depend on the visuals of the bar and the prices.
for example maybe you can upgrade your bar to look very luxurious, this would attract more wealthy clients who don't mind spending more.
simultaneously by changing the price you could influence how much clients buy, simple supply and demand action.

In my opinion having these more detailed modelling of clients' behavior is crucial to having depth to the game.

• As the tavern increases in appearance points, maybe higher ranking people come into the tavern such as nobles, knights and clerics? There could be some quirk to these characters perhaps. Maybe the Noble doesnt pay some of the time because they are w@nkers. 
• Serving the same customers too many times will cause them to pass out, or they get into a fight with another customer, which may break your table or decorations. The player will need to keep an eye on customer's unique features and see if you remember them continuously coming back to order, or maybe they start acting drunk/wobbly at their table so the player will also need to keep an eye on the seated customers at the same time.
• You could add weapons to the wall as decoration?
I don't develop games myself, I don't really want to suggest anything more because I don't know how hard these things are to implement, or if they are even any good.

textDisplay: One thing that really helps me is what I call the 1% rule. If you have a 0% day you will never ever finish. If you can convince yourself to have a 0.1% day you will finish eventually. I can almost always convince myself to start by telling myself "I'll just spend 15 min and see what I can do" and then I end up working on it for hours. Sometimes I just make a minor change and I am done for the day but more often than not it gets me going.
textOriginal: One thing that really helps me is what I call the 1% rule. If you have a 0% day you will never ever finish. If you can convince yourself to have a 0.1% day you will finish eventually. I can almost always convince myself to start by telling myself "I'll just spend 15 min and see what I can do" and then I end up working on it for hours. textDisplay: lol so many things you wont need to bother about using Unreal. Actually its better to start your first game there for a fast prototype. The goal should be making somethng playable FAST so you can iterate if your idea works in the first place, you can still make the actual game in unity once you know it works before wasting 99 years.Also you get to learn some general systems which you can replicate in unity later too if you still want to make the game there later.

textDisplay: 8:50 can you modify the walk animation to make it so they hold their mugs properly while walking?https://youtu.be/1dMoRECcstQYou can blend animations with an animation mask or an avatar mask. This allows you to select which bones are affected by an animation. In this situation the walk animation currently affects all bones so the right arm swings as normal. But if you were to place an avatar mask that only affects the right arm on this animation when the customer is holding a mug. you can either apply the same animation used for when they are sitting at a table, or create an animation of just the right arm holding a mug while walking. You should be able to just toggle this avatar mask on when the customer grabs the mug. A lot can be done with this technique.P. S. Don't do this right away, just put this conversation comment in your version control's issue tracker and get back to more important things.
textOriginal:
8:50 can you modify the walk animation to make it so they hold their mugs properly while walking?

https://youtu.be/1dMoRECcstQ
You can blend animations with an animation mask or an avatar mask. This allows you to select which bones are affected by an animation. In this situation the walk animation currently affects all bones so the right arm swings as normal. But if you were to place an avatar mask that only affects the right arm on this animation when the customer is holding a mug. you can either apply the same animation used for when they are sitting at a table, or create an animation of just the right arm holding a mug while walking. You should be able to just toggle this avatar mask on when the customer grabs the mug. A lot can be done with this technique.

P. S. Don't do this right away, just put this conversation comment in your version control's issue tracker and get back to more important things.
videoTitle: The worst part of being an indie game dev
cleaned_comment:
8:50 can you modify the walk animation to make it so they hold their mugs properly while walking?


you can blend animations with an animation mask or an avatar mask. this allows you to select which bones are affected by an animation. in this situation the walk animation currently affects all bones so the right arm swings as normal. but if you were to place an avatar mask that only affects the right arm on this animation when the customer is holding a mug. you can either apply the same animation used for when they are sitting at a table, or create an animation of just the right arm holding a mug while walking. you should be able to just toggle this avatar mask on when the customer grabs the mug. a lot can be done with this technique.

p. s. don't do this right away, just put this conversation comment in your version control's issue tracker and get back to more important things.

These are just a few suggestions to make the game feel more natural.

#1: I would add the health bar to the top left above the (Opening)

#2a: If the patron is drunk, they deplete their health more rapidly; the more they drink, the more tired and weaker they get.
#2b: If the patron is sober, they have more stamina and can then kick butt longer compared to the drunk ones.

Gets me in the mood to work on other projects as well.
